---
import Layout from '../../components/layout/Layout.astro';
import Aside from '../../components/handson/Aside.astro';

const locale = 'en';
const repo = 'theomonfort-org/Github-introduction-workshop';
const repoUrl = `https://github.com/${repo}`;
const accent = '#9bbc0f';
const shellStyle = `--entry-accent:${accent};--aside-accent:${accent}`;
---

<Layout locale={locale} currentPath="/handson2" title="Hands-on 2 — GitHub Core Capabilities">
  <style>
    /* Solo variant: no fixed TOC column, so drop the reserved left gutter. */
    .handson-shell--solo { max-width: 900px; }
    @media (min-width: 1024px) {
      .handson-shell--solo { padding-left: 1rem; }
    }
  </style>
  <section class="handson-shell handson-shell--solo" style={shellStyle}>
    <main class="handson-main">
      <header class="handson-step-header">
        <div class="handson-step-meta">
          <span class="handson-step-chip is-area font-pixel">🧭 GitHub Basics</span>
          <span class="handson-step-chip font-pixel">HANDS-ON 02</span>
          <span class="handson-step-chip font-pixel">⏱ ~45 min</span>
        </div>
        <h1 class="font-pixel-jp">Hands-on 2 — GitHub Core Capabilities</h1>
        <p class="handson-step-summary font-pixel-jp">
          Take a tiny Pomodoro app from repo to merged pull request while touching every
          core GitHub capability: Issues, Projects, Discussions, rulesets, Actions,
          secret scanning, CodeQL, and the review-and-merge flow.
        </p>
      </header>

      <article
        class="prose-akq handson-article"
        data-copy-label="COPY"
        data-copied-label="COPIED ✓"
        data-copy-aria="Copy code"
      >
        <Aside type="reference" accent={accent}>
          <p><strong>📦 Workshop repository</strong>: <a href={repoUrl}>{repo}</a></p>
          <p>
            A no-build Pomodoro timer written in plain HTML, CSS, and JavaScript. It ships
            with unit tests, a CI workflow, deliberately planted secrets and
            vulnerabilities, and a ready-to-merge feature branch
            (<code>feature/task-label</code>).
          </p>
        </Aside>

        <h2>0 — Get set up</h2>
        <p>Clone the repo and run the app and its tests locally:</p>
        <pre><code>git clone {repoUrl}.git
cd Github-introduction-workshop
npm install
npm test        # Vitest — 11 passing on main
npm run dev     # open http://localhost:8080</code></pre>
        <p>
          The app logic lives in <code>src/timer.js</code> (pure, testable functions) and
          <code>src/app.js</code> (DOM wiring). Tests are in <code>test/timer.test.js</code>
          and run automatically on every pull request via
          <code>.github/workflows/test.yml</code>.
        </p>

        <Aside type="positive" accent={accent}>
          <p><strong>Why it matters</strong>: keeping logic pure (no DOM) is what makes the
          timer unit-testable. The CI workflow runs those exact tests on every PR so a
          regression can never silently reach <code>main</code>.</p>
        </Aside>

        <h2>1 — ISSUES: capture the work</h2>
        <p>Issues are the unit of work on GitHub. Create three feature ideas for the app.</p>

        <h3>1.1 — From the UI</h3>
        <ol>
          <li>Open the repo → <strong>Issues</strong> tab → <strong>New issue</strong>.</li>
          <li>Give it a clear title and an <strong>Acceptance criteria</strong> checklist in the body.</li>
          <li>Repeat for all three features.</li>
        </ol>

        <h3>1.2 — From the CLI</h3>
        <pre><code>gh issue create -R {repo} \
  --title "Customizable session durations" \
  --body "Let users configure work / short / long break lengths."

gh issue create -R {repo} \
  --title "Play a sound when a session ends" \
  --body "Audible chime + optional browser notification on every transition."

gh issue create -R {repo} \
  --title "Daily focus statistics" \
  --body "Show pomodoros completed today and over the last 7 days."</code></pre>

        <Aside type="positive" accent={accent}>
          <p><strong>Tip</strong>: write acceptance criteria as a task list
          (<code>- [ ] ...</code>). GitHub renders live checkboxes and shows a progress bar,
          and the same issue can later be dragged onto a project board.</p>
        </Aside>

        <h2>2 — PROJECTS: plan on a board and a timeline</h2>
        <p>
          A <strong>Project</strong> (Projects v2) turns a pile of issues into a plan you can
          see as a Kanban board <em>and</em> a roadmap.
        </p>

        <h3>2.1 — Create the project</h3>
        <pre><code>gh project create --owner theomonfort-org --title "Pomodoro Feature Roadmap"</code></pre>
        <p>Then add the three issues as items:</p>
        <pre><code>gh project item-add &lt;number&gt; --owner theomonfort-org \
  --url {repoUrl}/issues/1
# repeat for issues 2 and 3</code></pre>

        <h3>2.2 — Add the views</h3>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>Board</strong>: on the project, <strong>+ New view</strong> →
            <strong>Board</strong>, grouped by <strong>Status</strong>
            (Todo / In Progress / Done). Drag issues between columns.</li>
          <li><strong>Roadmap</strong>: <strong>+ New view</strong> →
            <strong>Roadmap</strong>. Add a <strong>Date</strong> field
            (e.g. <em>Target date</em>) so items lay out on a timeline:</li>
        </ol>
        <pre><code>gh project field-create &lt;number&gt; --owner theomonfort-org \
  --name "Target date" --data-type DATE</code></pre>

        <Aside type="negative">
          <p><strong>Heads up</strong>: <code>gh project</code> can create the project, items,
          and fields, but the Board / Roadmap <em>view layouts</em> are added in the web UI.
          Everything is stored on the same project, so the CLI and UI stay in sync.</p>
        </Aside>

        <h2>3 — DISCUSSIONS: brainstorm before you build</h2>
        <p>Discussions are threaded, forum-style conversations, ideal for open-ended ideas
        that aren't yet concrete work items.</p>
        <ol>
          <li>Enable them: repo <strong>Settings</strong> → <strong>General</strong> →
            <strong>Features</strong> → check <strong>Discussions</strong>.</li>
          <li>Open the <strong>Discussions</strong> tab → <strong>New discussion</strong> →
            category <strong>Ideas</strong> → post a brainstorming prompt.</li>
        </ol>
        <p>From the CLI:</p>
        <pre><code>gh api -X PATCH repos/{repo} -F has_discussions=true</code></pre>

        <Aside type="positive" accent={accent}>
          <p><strong>Issues vs Discussions</strong>: use an <strong>Issue</strong> for a
          concrete, actionable task with a clear "done". Use a <strong>Discussion</strong>
          for questions, ideas, and voting. Great discussions often graduate into issues.</p>
        </Aside>

        <h2>4 — RULESET: protect <code>main</code></h2>
        <p>
          A branch <strong>ruleset</strong> enforces how code reaches <code>main</code>. We
          require a pull request, a review, a passing test check, and clean code scanning.
        </p>
        <ol>
          <li>Repo <strong>Settings</strong> → <strong>Rules</strong> →
            <strong>Rulesets</strong> → <strong>New branch ruleset</strong>.</li>
          <li>Target the <strong>default branch</strong>, enforcement <strong>Active</strong>.</li>
          <li>Enable:
            <ul>
              <li><strong>Require a pull request before merging</strong> → 1 approval.</li>
              <li><strong>Require status checks to pass</strong> → add the
                <code>test</code> check.</li>
              <li><strong>Require code scanning results</strong> → CodeQL, alerts:
                <em>errors</em>, security alerts: <em>high or higher</em>.</li>
              <li><strong>Block force pushes</strong> and <strong>deletion</strong>.</li>
            </ul>
          </li>
          <li>(Optional) Turn on <strong>automatic Copilot code review</strong> so every PR is
            reviewed by Copilot the moment it opens.</li>
        </ol>

        <Aside type="negative">
          <p><strong>Now direct pushes to <code>main</code> are blocked</strong> — even for
          admins. From here on, all changes must go through a pull request. That is exactly
          the point of a ruleset.</p>
        </Aside>

        <h2>5 — ADVANCED SECURITY: turn on code scanning</h2>
        <p>
          <strong>Secret scanning</strong> and <strong>CodeQL code scanning</strong> are free
          on public repos. Enable them from <strong>Settings</strong> →
          <strong>Advanced Security</strong>:
        </p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Secret scanning</strong> + <strong>Push protection</strong> → catches
            committed credentials and blocks new ones at push time.</li>
          <li><strong>CodeQL analysis</strong> → <strong>Set up</strong> →
            <strong>Default</strong> → <strong>Enable</strong>.</li>
        </ul>
        <p>What they find in this repo:</p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Secret scanning</strong>: the fake Google API key in
            <code>src/config.js</code> → an alert under <strong>Security → Secret scanning</strong>.</li>
          <li><strong>CodeQL</strong>: a DOM-based XSS in <code>src/app.js</code>
            (a URL parameter written with <code>innerHTML</code>) → a high-severity alert
            under <strong>Security → Code scanning</strong>.</li>
        </ul>

        <Aside type="negative">
          <p><strong>Push protection is real</strong>: try committing a fake Slack webhook or
          AWS key and pushing. GitHub rejects the push before the secret ever reaches the
          remote. The Google-key alert above exists only because that pattern isn't
          push-blocked — a nice illustration of the two layers working together.</p>
        </Aside>

        <h2>6 — PULL REQUEST: review, fix, merge</h2>
        <p>
          The branch <code>feature/task-label</code> adds a "current task" label and a
          "pomodoros until a long break" countdown. Open it as a PR into <code>main</code>:
        </p>
        <pre><code>gh pr create -R {repo} \
  --base main --head feature/task-label \
  --title "Add current-task label and long-break countdown"</code></pre>

        <h3>6.1 — Watch the checks fail (on purpose)</h3>
        <ul>
          <li>❌ <strong>Test</strong> — the CI workflow runs Vitest and fails: a bug in
            <code>pomodorosUntilLongBreak()</code> returns the wrong number.</li>
          <li>❌ <strong>CodeQL</strong> — the new task label is rendered with
            <code>innerHTML</code>, introducing a fresh XSS the scan flags on the PR.</li>
          <li>💬 <strong>Copilot code review</strong> comments automatically (if enabled in
            the ruleset).</li>
        </ul>
        <p>The ruleset keeps the <strong>Merge</strong> button disabled while either check is red.</p>

        <h3>6.2 — Fix the test bug</h3>
        <p>In <code>src/timer.js</code>, the countdown should return how many pomodoros
        <em>remain</em> before the next long break:</p>
        <pre><code>// Before (buggy)
export function pomodorosUntilLongBreak(completed, every = DEFAULTS.longBreakEvery) &#123;
  return completed % every;
&#125;

// After (fixed)
export function pomodorosUntilLongBreak(completed, every = DEFAULTS.longBreakEvery) &#123;
  return every - (completed % every);
&#125;</code></pre>

        <h3>6.3 — Fix the XSS</h3>
        <p>In <code>src/app.js</code>, render user text as text, not HTML:</p>
        <pre><code>// Before (vulnerable)
els.taskLabel.innerHTML = value ? `🎯 Working on: $&#123;value&#125;` : '';

// After (safe)
els.taskLabel.textContent = value ? `🎯 Working on: $&#123;value&#125;` : '';</code></pre>

        <Aside type="positive" accent={accent}>
          <p><strong>Why <code>textContent</code></strong>: it writes the value as literal
          text, so a task name like <code>&lt;img src=x onerror=alert(1)&gt;</code> shows up
          as characters instead of executing. CodeQL stops flagging the line because the
          untrusted data no longer reaches an HTML sink.</p>
        </Aside>

        <h3>6.4 — Commit, verify, merge</h3>
        <pre><code>git commit -am "Fix long-break countdown and render task label safely"
git push</code></pre>
        <ul>
          <li>✅ The <strong>Test</strong> check goes green (13 passing).</li>
          <li>✅ <strong>CodeQL</strong> re-runs and finds no new alerts.</li>
          <li>Get the required approval, then <strong>Merge pull request</strong>. 🎉</li>
        </ul>

        <hr />
        <h2>🏆 Quest clear</h2>
        <p>You created issues, planned them on a board and a timeline, opened a discussion,
        protected <code>main</code> with a ruleset, enabled Advanced Security, and drove a
        pull request through automated tests, CodeQL, and review all the way to merge — the
        complete GitHub core loop, start to finish.</p>
      </article>
    </main>
  </section>

  <script>
    (() => {
      // Open external links in a new tab (keep in-page anchors in place).
      const enhanceLinks = () => {
        document.querySelectorAll<HTMLAnchorElement>('.handson-article a[href]').forEach((a) => {
          const href = a.getAttribute('href') ?? '';
          if (!href || href.startsWith('#')) return;
          a.setAttribute('target', '_blank');
          a.setAttribute('rel', 'noopener noreferrer');
        });
      };

      // Inject a copy button into every code block.
      const enhanceCopyButtons = () => {
        const article = document.querySelector('.handson-article') as HTMLElement | null;
        if (!article) return;
        const copyLabel = article.dataset.copyLabel ?? 'COPY';
        const copiedLabel = article.dataset.copiedLabel ?? 'COPIED ✓';
        article.querySelectorAll<HTMLPreElement>('pre').forEach((pre) => {
          if (pre.dataset.copyEnhanced === '1') return;
          pre.dataset.copyEnhanced = '1';
          const btn = document.createElement('button');
          btn.type = 'button';
          btn.className = 'handson-copy-btn';
          btn.textContent = copyLabel;
          btn.setAttribute('aria-label', article.dataset.copyAria ?? copyLabel);
          let resetTimer: number | undefined;
          btn.addEventListener('click', async (event) => {
            event.preventDefault();
            const codeEl = pre.querySelector('code');
            const text = (codeEl?.textContent ?? pre.textContent ?? '').replace(/\s+$/, '');
            try {
              if (navigator.clipboard && window.isSecureContext) {
                await navigator.clipboard.writeText(text);
              } else {
                const ta = document.createElement('textarea');
                ta.value = text;
                ta.setAttribute('readonly', '');
                ta.style.position = 'fixed';
                ta.style.opacity = '0';
                document.body.appendChild(ta);
                ta.select();
                document.execCommand('copy');
                document.body.removeChild(ta);
              }
              btn.textContent = copiedLabel;
              btn.classList.add('is-copied');
              if (resetTimer) window.clearTimeout(resetTimer);
              resetTimer = window.setTimeout(() => {
                btn.textContent = copyLabel;
                btn.classList.remove('is-copied');
              }, 1800);
            } catch {
              /* user can still copy manually */
            }
          });
          pre.appendChild(btn);
        });
      };

      const run = () => {
        enhanceLinks();
        enhanceCopyButtons();
      };
      run();
      document.addEventListener('astro:page-load', run);
    })();
  </script>
</Layout>
